What led you to set it up?

00:01:11.309 --> 00:01:15.279
Well, first off, hello.
It's always best to greet people.

00:01:15.279 --> 00:01:17.309
- That's a good start.
- Exactly.

00:01:17.309 --> 00:01:21.789
In fact, it began

00:01:21.789 --> 00:01:25.399
at a dinner, when I was a soccer
player in Barcelona in 2008.

00:01:27.104 --> 00:01:30.189
There was a man next to me,
a gentleman of a certain age.

00:01:30.189 --> 00:01:32.589
He asked me questions, saying:

00:01:32.589 --> 00:01:35.309
"What are you 
going to do when you're older?"

00:01:35.309 --> 00:01:38.309
Because I was at the end of my career.

00:01:38.309 --> 00:01:41.309
So, he thought soccer was great,
but it was for children.

00:01:41.309 --> 00:01:43.709
"So, what are you going 
to do when you're older?"

00:01:43.709 --> 00:01:47.309
And the answer 
I gave him was childish, I said

00:01:47.309 --> 00:01:49.309
"Well, when I'm older,
I'm going to change the world."

00:01:49.309 --> 00:01:51.309
He said, "How will you change the world?"

00:01:51.309 --> 00:01:53.309
I said, "I would like to go into schools

00:01:53.309 --> 00:01:56.309
and discuss racism, sexism,
and homophobia

00:01:56.309 --> 00:01:59.309
to tell people you aren't born racist,
you become it.

00:01:59.309 --> 00:02:02.309
In fact, it's cultural conditioning."

00:02:02.309 --> 00:02:05.946
People often aren't aware of this.

00:02:06.946 --> 00:02:08.946
He said, "OK, what does that mean?"

00:02:08.946 --> 00:02:12.839
I said, "For example,
tell me what black people are like?"

00:02:12.839 --> 00:02:15.909
And so he replied, 
"OK, black people are like this or like that."

00:02:15.909 --> 00:02:18.479
I said, "That is how racism starts."

00:02:18.479 --> 00:02:20.309
When we think we know what someone

00:02:20.309 --> 00:02:24.309
will be like based on the color of their 
skin, their sexuality, or their gender.

00:02:24.309 --> 00:02:26.309
And then I gave him a few examples

00:02:26.309 --> 00:02:28.659
and when he left he said

00:02:28.659 --> 00:02:30.169
"Mr. Thuram,
I'm older than you.

00:02:30.169 --> 00:02:32.309
You ought to know
we can't change the world."

00:02:32.309 --> 00:02:34.959
And a few weeks later,
my telephone rang

00:02:34.959 --> 00:02:37.729
It was that same man, 
and he said, "You know what?

00:02:37.729 --> 00:02:41.309
You have already changed someone."
And that's what gave me the idea

00:02:41.309 --> 00:02:47.417
to set up a foundation
because he was the president of a...

00:02:48.142 --> 00:02:49.815
of DDB Spain.

00:02:49.815 --> 00:02:52.815
They're a leading advertising agency.

00:02:52.815 --> 00:02:55.815
And so, little by little,
I set up this foundation.

00:02:55.815 --> 00:02:59.826
And we have been visiting
schools for 10 years now

00:02:59.826 --> 00:03:01.405
in France, and in other countries.

00:03:01.405 --> 00:03:04.471
We're always trying to 
challenge public perception.

00:03:04.471 --> 00:03:07.103
The basic premise of the foundation

00:03:07.103 --> 00:03:09.172
is "you aren't born racist,
you become one."

00:03:09.172 --> 00:03:11.559
That's the idea behind
Education against Racism.

00:03:11.559 --> 00:03:14.656
You present this as part of your personal
story as something

00:03:14.656 --> 00:03:16.007
instinctive, a feeling.

00:03:16.007 --> 00:03:19.399
Have you researched this premise?

00:03:19.399 --> 00:03:22.089
How did you get to it?
Is it just experience

00:03:22.089 --> 00:03:23.709
or have there also been studies

00:03:23.709 --> 00:03:25.947
that support this point of view?

00:03:25.947 --> 00:03:29.001
First, it comes from a lived experience

00:03:29.001 --> 00:03:31.947
because I was born
in the Antilles, in Guadeloupe.

00:03:31.947 --> 00:03:36.749
I came to Ile-de-France in 1981

00:03:36.749 --> 00:03:38.881
when I was nine years old.

00:03:38.881 --> 00:03:42.290
And I always say
I became Black when I was nine.

00:03:42.290 --> 00:03:44.989
It seems surprising, but you become black.

00:03:44.989 --> 00:03:47.058
You become black in the eyes of the other.

00:03:47.058 --> 00:03:49.597
And the really interesting thing is that

00:03:49.597 --> 00:03:53.948
when you become black, 
you understand that it's a trivial thing.

00:03:53.948 --> 00:03:57.602
It's a very negative thing.
Some of my classmates

00:03:57.602 --> 00:04:01.645
named me after a cartoon...

00:04:01.645 --> 00:04:04.895
You are very young,
so you wouldn't know it.

00:04:04.895 --> 00:04:06.644
Sorry, I'm showing my age.

00:04:06.644 --> 00:04:09.644
It was called...
They called me "la Noiraude."

00:04:09.644 --> 00:04:11.781
Does anyone know
the cartoon "La Noiraude?"

00:04:11.781 --> 00:04:14.781
- Yeah
- Oh yeah.

00:04:14.781 --> 00:04:17.781
You read that too? OK.

00:04:17.781 --> 00:04:20.047
But, that's scary, they're really young.

00:04:20.047 --> 00:04:23.601
He's been saying, 
"They're really young" for 20 minutes.

00:04:23.601 --> 00:04:27.273
- I think that's really shocked him.
- It's extremely disconcerting.

00:04:27.273 --> 00:04:31.821
Well, there was a really stupid black cow.

00:04:31.821 --> 00:04:34.542
It makes you wonder
why the black cow was stupid

00:04:34.542 --> 00:04:39.134
while the white cow was very intelligent,
and I really didn't understand at all.

00:04:39.134 --> 00:04:41.765
And I remember I went home one day

00:04:41.765 --> 00:04:44.070
and I asked my mum

00:04:44.070 --> 00:04:47.332
why black people are viewed negatively.

00:04:47.332 --> 00:04:50.116
And she gave me a very bad answer.

00:04:50.116 --> 00:04:51.776
She said, "That's the way it is.

00:04:51.776 --> 00:04:53.939
People are racist. That won't change."

00:04:53.939 --> 00:04:56.461
And the thing with that was
that it meant that everyone was racist

00:04:56.461 --> 00:04:57.918
and it was unavoidable.

00:04:57.918 --> 00:05:01.989
So after that, I looked into it more
and spoke to some people.

00:05:01.989 --> 00:05:04.273
and I also began to understand my own family better.

00:05:04.273 --> 00:05:06.193
Because I started out 
with a lot of questions.

00:05:06.193 --> 00:05:08.170
As I said, I'm from the Antilles.

00:05:08.170 --> 00:05:10.753
We are a slightly non-conventional family.

00:05:10.753 --> 00:05:13.800
We were five children
from five different dads.

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:15.180
And none of them were around.

00:05:15.180 --> 00:05:17.182
So I also had to ask myself

00:05:17.182 --> 00:05:19.449
why is my family like this?

00:05:19.449 --> 00:05:23.839
Because I was faced
with another way of being a family

00:05:23.839 --> 00:05:24.838
in the Ile-de-France,

00:05:24.838 --> 00:05:27.621
and so I came across 
the history of slavery

00:05:27.621 --> 00:05:30.528
which was a very
unsettling story

00:05:30.528 --> 00:05:33.697
but after I did some research
and I understood that

00:05:33.697 --> 00:05:36.949
it was not a power relationship

00:05:36.949 --> 00:05:39.949
that white people or black people wanted

00:05:39.949 --> 00:05:44.306
but above all,
it was a concept.

00:05:44.726 --> 00:05:46.161
It was about economics.

00:05:46.161 --> 00:05:47.712
It was an economic construct.

00:05:47.712 --> 00:05:50.712
And economic
constructs involve domination.

00:05:50.712 --> 00:05:53.576
Through domination, 
you create a discourse.

00:05:53.576 --> 00:05:55.119
So, we created a whole discourse

00:05:55.119 --> 00:05:58.119
categorizing people 
according to their skin color.

00:05:58.119 --> 00:06:02.556
And this hierarchy 
still exists in today's societies.

00:06:02.556 --> 00:06:05.599
It is exactly the same thing
between men and women.

00:06:05.599 --> 00:06:09.102
It's because of a political construct

00:06:09.102 --> 00:06:12.102
that our society

00:06:12.102 --> 00:06:15.922
still teaches men to think
they are superior to women.

00:06:15.932 --> 00:06:19.735
That's whyâ€”this comes from
your personal story, again

00:06:19.735 --> 00:06:21.961
I saw that the foundation
relies on

00:06:21.961 --> 00:06:24.961
a committee of scientists, 
and anthropologists, etc.

00:06:24.961 --> 00:06:26.896
Have they helped back up the statement

00:06:26.896 --> 00:06:28.996
"you aren't born racist, you become it."

00:06:28.996 --> 00:06:30.848
or have they researched other things?

00:06:30.848 --> 00:06:32.162
In fact, first of all,

00:06:32.162 --> 00:06:34.852
We have all of the knowledge
needed to understand racism.

00:06:34.852 --> 00:06:36.202
Because, effectively,

00:06:36.202 --> 00:06:38.453
even the subjects of racism,

00:06:38.453 --> 00:06:40.988
don't generally understand 
what is happening

00:06:40.988 --> 00:06:42.316
or what causes it.

00:06:42.316 --> 00:06:44.516
So, I think it's very important

00:06:44.516 --> 00:06:46.915
to include intellectuals 
and they help

00:06:46.915 --> 00:06:49.685
to enrich my own way of thinking as well

00:06:49.685 --> 00:06:52.568
so that when 
I'm talking to children in particular

00:06:52.568 --> 00:06:54.039
I can be quite specific.

00:06:54.039 --> 00:06:55.825
For example, we have Mr. Yves Coppens

00:06:55.825 --> 00:06:58.385
and Ms FranÃ§oise HÃ©ritier, 
who has sadly passed away.

00:06:58.385 --> 00:07:02.190
And there are psychologists
as well, which is very important for me

00:07:02.190 --> 00:07:04.637
because, more than anything else, racism

00:07:04.637 --> 00:07:07.937
is often an unconscious feeling.

00:07:07.937 --> 00:07:09.253
And we don't control it.

00:07:09.253 --> 00:07:11.944
So, it's very interesting
to look at every aspect

00:07:11.944 --> 00:07:14.273
to understand this question.

00:07:14.943 --> 00:07:17.321
The particularly interesting thing

00:07:17.321 --> 00:07:19.311
about the foundation's perspective

00:07:19.311 --> 00:07:20.855
it is the idea of unlearning.

00:07:20.855 --> 00:07:22.445
There's a great literary movement

00:07:22.445 --> 00:07:24.713
lots of people have read
Sapiens in particular

00:07:24.713 --> 00:07:28.115
which aims to give us
a different perspective

00:07:28.115 --> 00:07:30.004
on the history, or
the hierarchization

00:07:30.004 --> 00:07:32.434
according to race, of man/woman.

00:07:32.564 --> 00:07:34.176
It's all forms of discrimination.

00:07:34.176 --> 00:07:36.416
Because the foundation deals with
every type

00:07:36.416 --> 00:07:38.148
of discrimination and equality...

00:07:38.148 --> 00:07:41.598
...the caste system. 
So unlearning is an interesting approach.

00:07:41.598 --> 00:07:45.694
How do you start?
Who does it start with? How far can it go?

00:07:45.694 --> 00:07:47.469
Unlearning is a major project.

00:07:47.469 --> 00:07:50.022
But first you must 
recognize that categories exist.

00:07:50.022 --> 00:07:53.161
We have created
categories throughout history.

00:07:53.161 --> 00:07:55.741
If you are aware of that,
that's a good start.

00:07:55.741 --> 00:07:59.049
For example, men/women,
that's a category, it's not harmless.

00:07:59.049 --> 00:08:01.782
If you are a man

00:08:01.782 --> 00:08:06.724
you need to know that
you're likely to think...

00:08:06.724 --> 00:08:09.517
I'm not talking about the men in here.

00:08:09.517 --> 00:08:11.508
I'm talking about other men.

00:08:13.658 --> 00:08:16.279
You might think that you are
superior to women.

00:08:16.279 --> 00:08:18.364
And women can also
subscribe to a similar logic

00:08:18.364 --> 00:08:20.894
by thinking that there are 
things that are not for them.

00:08:20.894 --> 00:08:23.883
And it's similar with
the color of your skin

00:08:23.883 --> 00:08:25.806
There are associated categories.

00:08:26.186 --> 00:08:29.273
And I think that to begin with

00:08:29.273 --> 00:08:30.793
if you are aware of that,

00:08:30.793 --> 00:08:34.183
you know that we don't
have the same experience of society,

00:08:34.183 --> 00:08:36.676
We don't describe history in the same way.

00:08:36.676 --> 00:08:42.186
For example, whether you are called
western or non-western

00:08:42.186 --> 00:08:44.428
that also changes the way history is told.

00:08:44.428 --> 00:08:49.570
I use examples with
the children, obviously.

00:08:49.570 --> 00:08:51.275
You know that this isn't true.

00:08:51.275 --> 00:08:52.555
I ask the children

00:08:52.555 --> 00:08:54.958
"Do you know Christopher Columbus?"

00:08:54.958 --> 00:08:56.978
The children say, "Yes, what about him?"

00:08:56.978 --> 00:08:59.346
I say, "Are you sure you know who he is?"

00:08:59.346 --> 00:09:01.913
They say, "Of course, Mr. Thuram."
I say, "Who is he?"

00:09:01.913 --> 00:09:03.588
"He discovered America."

00:09:03.588 --> 00:09:06.248
I say, "Really?
OK, kids, let's play a little game.

00:09:06.248 --> 00:09:08.665
"Imagine you're in the classroom

00:09:08.665 --> 00:09:11.871
and someone opens the door
and says I've discovered the classroom."

00:09:11.871 --> 00:09:13.805
The children say, "That's not right."

00:09:13.805 --> 00:09:16.178
I say, "But why not?"
They say, "We we're already there."

00:09:16.178 --> 00:09:18.558
And I say, "But when Columbus
reached the Americas,

00:09:18.558 --> 00:09:20.668
there were 80 million Native Americans."

00:09:20.668 --> 00:09:22.268
And they respond, "Oh yeah."

00:09:22.268 --> 00:09:24.297
But it's how we tell the story.

00:09:24.297 --> 00:09:28.365
And that's very interesting, and if 
you're not aware of this conditioning

00:09:28.365 --> 00:09:31.278
you can't understand 
the mechanisms of racism.

00:09:31.278 --> 00:09:35.824
If, for example, you haven't heard of
the Code Noir [Black Code]

00:09:35.824 --> 00:09:39.654
you can't really understand racism.

00:09:39.654 --> 00:09:41.548
Who here has heard of the Code Noir?

00:09:44.488 --> 00:09:46.925
The majority, I see, that's very good.

00:09:46.925 --> 00:09:49.852
That can go on the website,
if it goes like that.

00:09:49.852 --> 00:09:52.818
- In fact...
- That will be edited in the video.

00:09:53.058 --> 00:09:56.829
It's very interesting because
the Code Noir is really interesting.

00:09:56.829 --> 00:09:58.570
Being from the Antilles

00:09:58.570 --> 00:10:03.090
I had to know the Code Noir,
it was like the civil code for

00:10:03.090 --> 00:10:05.387
how black people were treated

00:10:05.387 --> 00:10:06.837
during slavery.

00:10:06.837 --> 00:10:11.119
So, the Code Noir started
in 1685 and ended in 1848.

00:10:11.119 --> 00:10:13.056
And so you can see that black people

00:10:13.056 --> 00:10:15.516
weren't considered to be human beings.

00:10:15.516 --> 00:10:17.703
They were seen as property.

00:10:17.703 --> 00:10:21.105
But, because that lasted such a long time

00:10:21.105 --> 00:10:23.574
it ended up being a habit.

00:10:23.574 --> 00:10:27.455
If you don't understand that
the Code Noir ended in 1848

00:10:27.455 --> 00:10:29.851
and that's extremely close to our times

00:10:29.851 --> 00:10:33.966
you won't understand
the mentalities we see today.

00:10:33.966 --> 00:10:37.562
For example, I often say that
my grandfather was born in 1908

00:10:37.562 --> 00:10:40.842
60 years after the abolition of slavery,
because there as well

00:10:40.842 --> 00:10:44.318
we think of slavery as not really being
connected to us.

00:10:44.318 --> 00:10:49.148
But that means that I was born
a few generations after slavery

00:10:49.148 --> 00:10:51.356
so if we don't recognize that

00:10:51.356 --> 00:10:52.736
we can't understand.

00:10:52.746 --> 00:10:54.946
If you don't know the 
Code de l'indigÃ©nat [indigenous peoples' code]

00:10:54.946 --> 00:10:56.432
it's exactly the same thing.

00:10:56.432 --> 00:11:01.368
The Code de l'indigÃ©nat, is how 
they managed people in the colonies.

00:11:01.368 --> 00:11:03.904
And that ended in the 1950's.

00:11:03.904 --> 00:11:06.173
And in the 1950s

00:11:06.173 --> 00:11:09.860
there were still classes for 
ten-year-old children in school

00:11:09.860 --> 00:11:11.950
which taught them there was a hierarchy

00:11:11.950 --> 00:11:13.973
of people according to their skin color.

00:11:13.973 --> 00:11:17.018
And white people were superior.

00:11:17.018 --> 00:11:19.834
There's a gradation of color,
and black people

00:11:19.834 --> 00:11:22.596
are the missing link between
monkeys and humans.

00:11:22.596 --> 00:11:24.649
That's why, when I was a soccer player

00:11:24.649 --> 00:11:26.852
fans would make
monkey noises at me.

00:11:26.852 --> 00:11:28.882
They did not know this history

00:11:28.882 --> 00:11:32.998
but to them, 
making the link between black and monkey

00:11:32.998 --> 00:11:36.357
seemed normal.
Really, they had learned that.

00:11:36.357 --> 00:11:38.720
That's why I say
that it is very interesting

00:11:38.720 --> 00:11:41.720
to understand history
so you can unlearn it.

00:11:41.720 --> 00:11:44.604
To understand, in effect, how you work.

00:11:44.604 --> 00:11:46.407
That is, how we interact

00:11:46.407 --> 00:11:49.407
with each other, according to skin color

00:11:49.407 --> 00:11:53.307
disability, or whether
we are male or female,

00:11:53.307 --> 00:11:57.674
I mean there are, how can I say this...

00:11:57.674 --> 00:12:00.986
Relationships that you
don't understand sometimes.

00:12:00.986 --> 00:12:04.543
For example, here in France, in any case

00:12:04.543 --> 00:12:07.650
there is always this color barrier.

00:12:07.650 --> 00:12:09.359
People will say it's not true.

00:12:09.359 --> 00:12:14.753
But it is. I mean if 
we looked for diversity here

00:12:15.363 --> 00:12:17.659
who would represent diversity?

00:12:19.309 --> 00:12:20.659
For a French person?

00:12:21.279 --> 00:12:24.279
Do you represent diversity?

00:12:25.793 --> 00:12:28.323
You look diverse.

00:12:30.575 --> 00:12:34.137
It's the same if we look for
someone from a visible minority.

00:12:34.137 --> 00:12:37.543
That's you again. Sorry.

00:12:37.543 --> 00:12:40.314
OK, but if we say visible minority

00:12:40.314 --> 00:12:43.269
that means there's an invisible majority.

00:12:43.269 --> 00:12:45.317
And who are the invisible majority?

00:12:45.317 --> 00:12:47.456
White people.

00:12:47.456 --> 00:12:51.333
So we have made something up
about native French people.

00:12:51.333 --> 00:12:53.620
So, you are not native French.

00:12:53.620 --> 00:12:55.945
I can sense it, I don't know why.

00:12:55.945 --> 00:12:58.278
But we wouldn't class you as native.

00:12:58.278 --> 00:13:00.548
You mustn't sit next to me.

