This is just to show that
we don't really realize

00:13:06.152 --> 00:13:10.041
but there is often 
this barrier based on skin color.

00:13:10.041 --> 00:13:13.024
And there is another way of seeing things.

00:13:13.024 --> 00:13:16.158
And I think that the first thing
is to recognize that.

00:13:16.158 --> 00:13:20.567
And then, little by little, we can heal.

00:13:20.567 --> 00:13:23.345
The idea of becoming aware 
and unlearning is interesting.

00:13:23.345 --> 00:13:25.027
So my question to you is

00:13:25.027 --> 00:13:28.027
â€”because it's called
"education against racism"â€”

00:13:28.027 --> 00:13:31.578
what do you learn after that?
Because there's a risk of relearning

00:13:31.578 --> 00:13:34.178
a model that, could become in...

00:13:34.178 --> 00:13:37.020
20 or 40 years yet another failure.

00:13:37.020 --> 00:13:38.541
Or what do you do to teach

00:13:38.541 --> 00:13:42.471
a vision that is sufficiently broad
that you can impose it without any danger?

00:13:42.471 --> 00:13:44.531
So, if we class ourselves 
as a human beings

00:13:44.531 --> 00:13:46.481
when writing history, that's interesting.

00:13:46.481 --> 00:13:50.644
So we step outside the hierarchies,
because very often

00:13:50.644 --> 00:13:53.204
when I talk to you about
Christopher Columbus,

00:13:53.204 --> 00:13:56.368
you know the story. 
There were many people.

00:13:56.368 --> 00:14:00.829
But, the others didn't
really exist until we discovered them.

00:14:00.829 --> 00:14:02.708
Or until we saw them.

00:14:02.708 --> 00:14:05.819
I think it would be interesting 
when talking about Columbus...

00:14:05.819 --> 00:14:09.713
Who here, for example, has heard of
the Valladolid debate?

00:14:11.691 --> 00:14:14.756
No one. It's very interesting to
understand that as well.

00:14:14.756 --> 00:14:16.458
The topic in question was

00:14:16.458 --> 00:14:19.758
"Do Native Americans have a soul like us?"

00:14:20.008 --> 00:14:21.940
Because that's what's interesting.

00:14:21.940 --> 00:14:26.494
Showing that these questions of domination

00:14:26.494 --> 00:14:30.066
existed in the past and also exist today.

00:14:30.066 --> 00:14:35.315
What does European society
think about the world?

00:14:35.315 --> 00:14:38.228
Does the world belong to everyone?

00:14:40.590 --> 00:14:41.863
Who does the world belong to?

00:14:42.768 --> 00:14:43.870
- It's a good question.
- It is.

00:14:43.870 --> 00:14:46.723
But it doesn't belong to everyone,
believe me.

00:14:46.723 --> 00:14:48.717
I don't want to spoil the mood.

00:14:48.717 --> 00:14:50.437
But it does not belong to everyone.

00:14:50.437 --> 00:14:55.480
There are some people who just
have to do what other people have decided

00:14:55.480 --> 00:14:58.480
to do, and follow them.

00:14:58.480 --> 00:15:01.480
Because there is a model to follow.

00:15:01.480 --> 00:15:05.593
And it was mostly us
who established that model.

00:15:05.593 --> 00:15:09.687
And again today, we end up 
thinking that we are dominant

00:15:09.687 --> 00:15:11.557
and it's right for us to be dominant

00:15:11.557 --> 00:15:13.241
because we're better than the rest.

00:15:13.241 --> 00:15:15.382
It's always this trick of...

00:15:15.382 --> 00:15:19.661
changing your perspective,
because very often

00:15:19.661 --> 00:15:22.984
we begin by thinking that we are
at the center

00:15:22.984 --> 00:15:26.019
and that we are right, us.

00:15:26.019 --> 00:15:29.517
But we often don't have a global
vision of world history.

00:15:30.407 --> 00:15:33.222
But I think that history

00:15:33.222 --> 00:15:35.159
should be told differently.

00:15:35.159 --> 00:15:37.579
Yes, told differently. OK.

00:15:37.579 --> 00:15:40.985
I'm going to explore
the foundation's work a bit more.

00:15:40.985 --> 00:15:44.742
I saw that there were four pillars
that make up your work:

00:15:44.742 --> 00:15:47.453
equality, individuality,
education and remebrance.

00:15:47.453 --> 00:15:50.123
Could you tell us a bit
more about each of those pillars?

00:15:50.123 --> 00:15:52.523
How you handle them
within this idea of education.

00:15:52.523 --> 00:15:53.714
How you approach them.

00:15:53.714 --> 00:15:57.353
Well, the idea of being unique.

00:15:57.353 --> 00:16:00.227
It seems silly, but

00:16:00.227 --> 00:16:03.228
since the dawn of time

00:16:03.228 --> 00:16:07.538
when we tell the story of racism,
sexism, or homophobia

00:16:07.538 --> 00:16:12.335
we forget that every one of us is unique.

00:16:12.335 --> 00:16:14.539
We box people in

00:16:14.539 --> 00:16:15.779
according to skin color.

00:16:15.779 --> 00:16:17.861
When we talk about people with black skin

00:16:17.861 --> 00:16:21.197
it's, "black people 
all work in the same way."

00:16:21.197 --> 00:16:25.794
And when I'm with children

00:16:25.794 --> 00:16:28.402
not the very young ones,
because the very young ones

00:16:28.402 --> 00:16:30.621
are really pure anyway

00:16:30.621 --> 00:16:33.621
but with the older ones.
When I ask the question

00:16:33.621 --> 00:16:37.807
"Tell me what black people are like?",
there are some children who respond.

00:16:37.807 --> 00:16:41.414
It's awful.

00:16:41.414 --> 00:16:44.248
It's because, in their minds

00:16:44.248 --> 00:16:48.298
these people don't exist as individuals.

00:16:48.298 --> 00:16:51.037
They exist as a collective.

00:16:51.037 --> 00:16:55.334
It's like if you said, in these schools...

00:16:55.334 --> 00:16:57.687
"What are white people like?"

00:16:57.687 --> 00:17:01.065
They say,
"Well, they're like everyone else."

00:17:03.045 --> 00:17:05.925
That means they have characteristics of...
When I ask about Asians, they say

00:17:05.925 --> 00:17:08.925
"they play ping-pong, they are yellow."

00:17:08.925 --> 00:17:10.639
It's just to show that that exists.

00:17:10.639 --> 00:17:15.894
It's the children who 
grow up with ideas about color.

00:17:15.894 --> 00:17:17.104
And that's interesting.

00:17:17.104 --> 00:17:19.805
That's why I say
we really need to teach people

00:17:19.805 --> 00:17:23.569
to understand that
every one of us is unique.

00:17:23.569 --> 00:17:29.329
And when we talk, for example,
about French culture, because...

00:17:29.329 --> 00:17:32.084
what is French culture?

00:17:32.084 --> 00:17:35.084
Who is French here?

00:17:35.084 --> 00:17:36.681
Everyone? I can't tell.

00:17:36.681 --> 00:17:39.365
Listen... Because I can see
some people aren't listening

00:17:39.365 --> 00:17:40.888
so, I thought...

00:17:40.888 --> 00:17:43.080
Right, the majority, OK.

00:17:43.080 --> 00:17:46.657
We're all agreed that
I am Antillean, I am French.

00:17:46.657 --> 00:17:50.657
There are people who are Breton
or Alsatian

00:17:50.657 --> 00:17:53.486
for whom French culture is complex.

00:17:53.486 --> 00:17:57.187
But even in the Antilles,
we don't all have the same culture.

00:17:57.187 --> 00:17:59.295
It's something personal.

00:17:59.295 --> 00:18:02.796
And sometimes that unsettles me.

00:18:02.796 --> 00:18:07.196
We would like to say
that there is a French culture

00:18:07.196 --> 00:18:09.709
a French way of being.

00:18:09.709 --> 00:18:13.819
And so we say, "you will need
to integrate into French culture."

00:18:13.819 --> 00:18:14.734
But which one?

00:18:15.734 --> 00:18:17.734
Which one?

00:18:17.734 --> 00:18:19.309
The odds are already against you.

00:18:19.309 --> 00:18:25.258
And so we need to come back to this:
every one of us has our own culture.

00:18:25.258 --> 00:18:27.798
And we need to recognize that as well.

00:18:27.798 --> 00:18:29.625
That's why I talk about individuality.

00:18:29.625 --> 00:18:31.665
Because that is the problem of racism.

00:18:31.665 --> 00:18:35.431
He is black, he is like this.
He is white, he is like that.

00:18:35.431 --> 00:18:38.533
But that doesn't make sense.
That's a man, he is like this.

00:18:38.533 --> 00:18:40.504
And I think it's really important

00:18:40.504 --> 00:18:44.692
to develop that in children.

00:18:44.692 --> 00:18:46.112
Then, remembrance...

00:18:46.112 --> 00:18:49.112
remembrance is very important to me
because, once again

00:18:49.112 --> 00:18:53.156
every one of us here is
the product of history.

00:18:53.156 --> 00:18:55.139
The product of the past.

00:18:55.139 --> 00:18:59.555
And we must remind children
that societies evolve

00:18:59.555 --> 00:19:01.611
because there have always
been men and women

00:19:01.611 --> 00:19:04.001
who have said no to injustice.

00:19:04.001 --> 00:19:07.351
And I think it is very important
to recognize that.

00:19:07.351 --> 00:19:09.387
Because people frequently say

00:19:09.387 --> 00:19:11.147
"No, nothing changes."

00:19:11.147 --> 00:19:14.619
Yes, things do change. I'm proof of that.

00:19:14.619 --> 00:19:17.682
I told you that 
my grandfather was born in 1908.

00:19:17.682 --> 00:19:20.318
Things have changed because

00:19:20.318 --> 00:19:24.746
there have always been people
who fought for freedom and equality.

00:19:24.746 --> 00:19:26.836
And we tell the kids something essential

00:19:26.836 --> 00:19:30.019
that freedom is won, it is not given.

00:19:31.214 --> 00:19:34.717
And so, we must be properly
prepared to fight for this equality

00:19:34.717 --> 00:19:37.967
so for me, remembrance is very important.

00:19:37.967 --> 00:19:39.308
And then there is...

00:19:39.308 --> 00:19:42.349
There was equality, individuality,
education. You've done lots.

00:19:42.349 --> 00:19:45.372
Equality, yes. That seems obvious to me.

00:19:45.372 --> 00:19:48.497
Often, when we talk to the children

00:19:48.497 --> 00:19:50.838
about equality,

00:19:50.838 --> 00:19:54.111
they really have a problem with
homosexuality, for example.

00:19:54.111 --> 00:19:58.834
OK, and whatever their religion,
we come up against,

00:19:58.834 --> 00:20:01.724
"Yeah, but they're not like us."

00:20:01.724 --> 00:20:03.606
But, when I say, "So, kids

00:20:03.606 --> 00:20:08.186
can one person 
have more rights than another

00:20:08.186 --> 00:20:09.974
in our society?"
... they say, "No."

00:20:09.974 --> 00:20:12.663
"Can an individual have fewer rights?"
"No."

00:20:12.663 --> 00:20:16.865
And I say, "OK, there you go.
That means you think

00:20:16.865 --> 00:20:19.671
that a homosexual
is not a human being like us."

00:20:19.671 --> 00:20:21.850
That's the problem with categories.

00:20:21.850 --> 00:20:23.453
They mean that sometimes,

00:20:23.453 --> 00:20:26.453
we don't see other people
as human beings like ourselves.

00:20:26.453 --> 00:20:28.741
We see them through their religion

00:20:28.741 --> 00:20:29.823
color, or sexuality.

00:20:29.823 --> 00:20:33.513
So that's why, in my opinion, equality
is always very important.

00:20:33.513 --> 00:20:36.719
And putting the human being
back at the heart of everything.

00:20:36.719 --> 00:20:38.448
When we talk about the human being

00:20:38.448 --> 00:20:40.998
it's actually easier
for the younger children.

00:20:40.998 --> 00:20:43.413
OK. So I wonder, because...

00:20:43.413 --> 00:20:49.248
In the organizations here in France
that represent minorities

00:20:49.248 --> 00:20:51.248
and diversity and the minority

00:20:51.248 --> 00:20:54.248
they are ensuring success,
helping them to achieve.

00:20:54.248 --> 00:20:56.147
But the minorities, they...

00:20:56.147 --> 00:20:59.933
Well, we're coming back to the 
invisible majority and visible minority.

00:20:59.933 --> 00:21:02.867
- No, no, but...
- I won't go back to that discussion...

00:21:02.867 --> 00:21:06.105
we would need more time...
- No, but it's interesting because

00:21:06.105 --> 00:21:09.974
the majority generally speaking,
people who make up the majority

00:21:09.974 --> 00:21:11.476
because if belong to a minority

00:21:11.476 --> 00:21:14.236
- they think... I don't know.
- I don't belong anywhere.

00:21:14.236 --> 00:21:19.605
You've talked about minorities,
but what is really interesting,

00:21:19.605 --> 00:21:21.884
is that people
who think they are the majority

00:21:21.884 --> 00:21:23.704
think that they are more legitimate.

00:21:23.704 --> 00:21:25.436
They wouldn't want to say it

00:21:25.436 --> 00:21:26.731
but it's true.

00:21:27.583 --> 00:21:30.925
I am part of the majority,
I am more legitimate.

00:21:30.925 --> 00:21:34.316
I am part of the minority,
I must keep out of the way.

00:21:34.316 --> 00:21:36.589
We mustn't form groups
in case it's a plot.

00:21:36.589 --> 00:21:37.893
you never know...

00:21:37.893 --> 00:21:39.156
Wait, what does that mean?

00:21:40.156 --> 00:21:42.156
OK? Well, it's interesting.

00:21:42.156 --> 00:21:44.179
Interesting in the sense that it's like a plot.

00:21:44.179 --> 00:21:45.179
Right.

00:21:45.179 --> 00:21:47.069
The front row are laughing at that.

00:21:47.069 --> 00:21:49.171
Because we're in a group,
we're plotting.

00:21:49.171 --> 00:21:51.167
You are plotting something.

00:21:52.224 --> 00:21:55.017
I'm going to tell you 
a quick story about "plotting".

00:21:55.424 --> 00:21:57.736
Because very often
we don't realize.

00:21:57.736 --> 00:22:01.176
When you are a so-called minority

00:22:01.176 --> 00:22:02.936
and have dark-brown skin,

00:22:02.936 --> 00:22:04.697
you are noticed...

00:22:05.277 --> 00:22:08.150
when your body comes into the equation,
you are noticed.

00:22:08.406 --> 00:22:11.458
Once, when I was
at with my soccer team

00:22:11.458 --> 00:22:15.359
we were "in the green", 
which is when you go to the hotel

00:22:15.359 --> 00:22:17.427
before a match to relax and all that.

00:22:17.427 --> 00:22:20.427
And so there was a big table

00:22:20.427 --> 00:22:23.003
and we were having dinner

00:22:23.003 --> 00:22:25.254
and my trainer arrived and said to us

00:22:25.254 --> 00:22:29.089
"You blacks,
you're always together.

00:22:30.459 --> 00:22:32.981
"It doesn't bother you,
you're always there together."

00:22:33.051 --> 00:22:34.482
He said that to me in Italian.

00:22:34.482 --> 00:22:37.009
I said, "Oh yeah, it's weird though,

00:22:37.009 --> 00:22:40.508
there are 4 of us black people here,
and there are 15 white people

00:22:40.508 --> 00:22:42.198
and we're in a group."

00:22:43.185 --> 00:22:45.023
"And they're in a group there as well."

00:22:45.023 --> 00:22:47.922
And the guy looked at us and then he left.

00:22:50.025 --> 00:22:52.590
No, but it's interesting.

00:22:53.644 --> 00:22:55.782
That's why I say that sometimes

00:22:55.782 --> 00:22:57.292
there are even guys who think

00:22:57.292 --> 00:22:59.168
"We can't be in a group.

00:22:59.168 --> 00:23:00.682
They'll think we're plotting.
Let's split."

00:23:01.550 --> 00:23:02.571
So, it's interesting.

00:23:02.571 --> 00:23:04.744
It's funny you have
so many stories like that

00:23:04.744 --> 00:23:08.666
both personal and from your research,
that you can tell the children.

00:23:08.666 --> 00:23:10.326
Tell me, when you talk to the kids

00:23:10.326 --> 00:23:13.980
what do you tell them are the keys
to getting on in society

00:23:13.980 --> 00:23:16.071
to be successful, in whatever way?

00:23:16.071 --> 00:23:18.932
Because unlearning
and relearning allows them

00:23:18.932 --> 00:23:20.803
to better integrate in society

00:23:20.803 --> 00:23:22.160
in the positive sense.

00:23:22.160 --> 00:23:25.305
How do you help them go further,
to realize that there is a place

00:23:25.305 --> 00:23:27.549
for them in society, a good place.

00:23:27.549 --> 00:23:30.791
Well, that is the most important thing.

00:23:30.791 --> 00:23:33.498
- Yes.
- Well, we call that

00:23:33.498 --> 00:23:35.312
self-esteem.

00:23:35.312 --> 00:23:37.780
It's what helps you get ahead in society.

00:23:37.780 --> 00:23:39.967
And that's why it's
extremely important

00:23:39.967 --> 00:23:42.927
to talk about racism in all its forms.

00:23:42.927 --> 00:23:45.463
Why? Because when people
are subject to racism

00:23:45.463 --> 00:23:48.369
it can affect their self-esteem.

00:23:48.369 --> 00:23:50.642
That means I don't belong

00:23:50.642 --> 00:23:53.013
or I feel inferior.

00:23:53.013 --> 00:23:54.955
And so the idea is to say, yes

00:23:54.955 --> 00:23:57.012
racism exists,

00:23:57.012 --> 00:24:00.297
however, you need to understand

00:24:00.297 --> 00:24:02.857
that you are not the problem

00:24:02.857 --> 00:24:03.833
the others are.

00:24:03.833 --> 00:24:05.858
So, when I was in Italy

00:24:05.858 --> 00:24:08.858
people made monkey noises on the pitch.

00:24:08.858 --> 00:24:11.871
I didn't doubt that there was a problem:

00:24:11.871 --> 00:24:13.330
it was the fans.

00:24:13.330 --> 00:24:15.174
And that is very important.

00:24:15.174 --> 00:24:17.834
Besides, this is what works
best with children.

00:24:17.834 --> 00:24:20.703
As soon as they understand it,
they say, "Oh, yeah."

00:24:20.703 --> 00:24:23.673
and whatever the problem is,
"you're fat, you're..."

00:24:23.673 --> 00:24:26.293
they know the other person
is the one with the problem.

00:24:26.293 --> 00:24:28.014
Because otherwise you'd never cope.

00:24:28.014 --> 00:24:32.177
And so, we also need to teach children

00:24:33.747 --> 00:24:37.219
how far they should accept
having to disguise themselves.

00:24:37.219 --> 00:24:40.117
Because, generally speaking, in life

00:24:40.117 --> 00:24:43.081
all of us are made to wear
disguises sometimes.

00:24:43.937 --> 00:24:47.693
The dominant category frequently

00:24:47.693 --> 00:24:51.067
asks you,
either consciously or unconsciously

00:24:51.067 --> 00:24:53.412
to resemble them.

00:24:53.412 --> 00:24:57.081
For example, we'll talk about
disguising your accent.

00:24:57.081 --> 00:24:59.632
Recently, I was at the house 
of some journalists

00:24:59.632 --> 00:25:01.384
and I said, "It's strange though,

00:25:01.384 --> 00:25:04.089
"on the TV, it seems like
there's only one accent."

00:25:04.089 --> 00:25:07.014
So there must be some
journalists who disguise themselves

00:25:07.014 --> 00:25:10.038
who have Southern accents,
and who have been told

00:25:10.038 --> 00:25:12.168
"Listen to your accent."

00:25:12.168 --> 00:25:13.168
And so, he said,

00:25:13.168 --> 00:25:15.694
"Oh yeah, that's true,
they did say that to me."

00:25:16.514 --> 00:25:19.899
And one of them said,
"Yeah, I say 'shore' with an accent

00:25:19.899 --> 00:25:21.822
so now I say 'coastline' instead."

00:25:23.786 --> 00:25:27.358
And so it's very interesting.
But you need to know, for example

00:25:27.358 --> 00:25:31.576
when you are called a minority

00:25:31.576 --> 00:25:33.437
that's why it's very interesting

00:25:33.437 --> 00:25:35.531
you're told
to disguise yourself sometimes.

00:25:35.531 --> 00:25:37.217
Your behavior.

00:25:38.704 --> 00:25:40.253
I don't want to shock anyone.

00:25:40.253 --> 00:25:41.572
Even sometimes the barber.

00:25:42.369 --> 00:25:43.931
For example, very often

00:25:43.931 --> 00:25:45.857
women hide their frizzy hair.

00:25:45.857 --> 00:25:49.597
Because, really, they look at

00:25:49.597 --> 00:25:53.486
the rules of beauty
and they don't see themselves.

00:25:53.486 --> 00:25:57.418
It's very interesting to think about that.

00:25:57.418 --> 00:25:59.720
And to know how far you go.

00:25:59.720 --> 00:26:03.337
For example, when I talk
about self-esteem

00:26:03.337 --> 00:26:06.086
In the United States, they did

00:26:07.491 --> 00:26:12.073
a test with dolls.
I don't know if you've heard of it?

00:26:12.397 --> 00:26:14.953
Do you know about the black dolls
and the white dolls?

00:26:16.001 --> 00:26:18.368
OK, you're not American, 
so that makes sense.

00:26:19.311 --> 00:26:21.671
Well, they did tests with children

00:26:21.671 --> 00:26:25.365
they said:
"Look, which doll is the most beautiful?

00:26:25.365 --> 00:26:27.894
"The prettiest? The naughtiest?"

00:26:29.062 --> 00:26:32.759
And the children attributed

00:26:32.759 --> 00:26:35.613
all of the negative qualities
to the black dolls.

00:26:36.629 --> 00:26:38.442
And at one point they said to them

00:26:38.442 --> 00:26:41.442
"But which doll looks like you?"

00:26:41.442 --> 00:26:45.343
And then they panicked
because the children were black.

00:26:46.465 --> 00:26:51.380
So, they had internalized the idea
that all bad things

00:26:51.380 --> 00:26:53.584
were their color, and on the film

00:26:53.584 --> 00:26:54.879
you can see they are upset.

00:26:54.879 --> 00:26:57.652
Because they suddenly realize thatâ€”oh no.

00:26:57.652 --> 00:27:01.494
That's why I say this is really serious

00:27:01.494 --> 00:27:04.818
because, more than anything else,
racism is really dangerous.

00:27:04.818 --> 00:27:09.507
Because you can internalize
a negative thought about yourself.

00:27:10.338 --> 00:27:13.325
And I frequently say to the children,

00:27:13.325 --> 00:27:17.128
"There are a lot of young
homosexuals who take their own lives.

00:27:17.128 --> 00:27:19.884
Do you know why?"

00:27:21.024 --> 00:27:24.968
And they say, "Yes, their parents."
No, it's because of us.

00:27:24.968 --> 00:27:29.344
Because we're the ones who cause them
to think negatively about themselves.

00:27:29.344 --> 00:27:32.415
And I say to them,
"The problem isn't homosexuality.

00:27:32.415 --> 00:27:34.115
The problem is us."

00:27:34.115 --> 00:27:37.385
So, we need grow up
thinking about that.

00:27:37.385 --> 00:27:41.254
Is it normal that every one of us

00:27:41.254 --> 00:27:44.602
has at some point driven people
to suicide with our behavior?

00:27:44.602 --> 00:27:45.602
That's why I think

00:27:46.935 --> 00:27:49.935
self-esteem is very important.

00:27:49.935 --> 00:27:53.229
Because for all of us

00:27:53.229 --> 00:27:55.693
it's what helps us get on in life.

00:27:55.693 --> 00:27:57.676
If I was a soccer player

00:27:57.676 --> 00:28:00.906
you have this idea that

00:28:00.906 --> 00:28:03.314
you could do it too.

00:28:03.314 --> 00:28:05.555
And you have this potential inside of you

00:28:05.555 --> 00:28:07.483
which will help you get on.

00:28:07.483 --> 00:28:11.541
And you really deserve it. Really, there
are so many things that come together.

00:28:11.541 --> 00:28:13.160
And sometimes unconsciously.

00:28:13.160 --> 00:28:17.246
And they push us, but there are children
who have a handicap from the start.

00:28:17.246 --> 00:28:21.765
Because they've been told,
their sexuality, or where they're from...

00:28:21.765 --> 00:28:25.321
for example, at the moment,
I have an exhibition

00:28:25.321 --> 00:28:29.709
in the Delacroix museum
in the 6th arrondissement of Paris

00:28:29.709 --> 00:28:33.163
and recently, there were some children
who had come from Sarcelle,

00:28:33.163 --> 00:28:34.645
they had come to see it.

00:28:34.645 --> 00:28:35.675
And so I said to them

00:28:35.675 --> 00:28:37.368
"What do you think of this area?"

00:28:37.368 --> 00:28:38.139
They said

00:28:38.639 --> 00:28:42.319
"It's weird here...
everyone speaks really quietly."

00:28:42.319 --> 00:28:45.431
"It's funny when they talk like that."

00:28:45.431 --> 00:28:48.141
"And why do they dress like that?"

00:28:48.141 --> 00:28:50.107
And I said, "Do you feel uncomfortable?"

00:28:50.107 --> 00:28:52.639
They said, "It's not for us here."

00:28:52.639 --> 00:28:54.018
And I said, "But the museum?"

00:28:54.018 --> 00:28:58.408
They said, "Yeah, but listen, 
this isn't our place."

00:28:58.408 --> 00:29:02.717
That's the problem.
Lots of children grow up thinking

00:29:02.717 --> 00:29:05.072
that they're not in the right place.

00:29:05.072 --> 00:29:07.447
And its extremely dangerous.
They can't succeed.

00:29:07.447 --> 00:29:12.834
And so the idea is to provide
the knowledge to change that.

00:29:12.872 --> 00:29:16.453
You've mentioned what you were doing
at the Delacroix museum.

00:29:16.453 --> 00:29:17.483
Any other things

00:29:17.483 --> 00:29:19.743
you've done you'd like
to talk about in detail?

00:29:19.743 --> 00:29:21.029
It's very interesting.

00:29:21.029 --> 00:29:23.419
Are there other activities
you'd like to describe?

00:29:23.419 --> 00:29:24.769
I'm looking at the time too

00:29:24.769 --> 00:29:27.015
to make sure our friends
can ask questions.

00:29:27.015 --> 00:29:30.395
Listen, at the moment we are working on

00:29:30.395 --> 00:29:34.845
an exhibition, L'Orient [The East]

00:29:34.845 --> 00:29:38.080
about the painter Delacroix,

00:29:38.080 --> 00:29:41.578
and we're showing to what extent,
when you look at a painting

00:29:41.578 --> 00:29:45.659
you need to place it
in its historical context.

00:29:45.659 --> 00:29:47.823
Because Delacroix actually traveled

00:29:47.823 --> 00:29:50.823
to the East, to Morocco and to Algeria.

00:29:50.823 --> 00:29:54.114
And it also shows that this
version of the East is fascinating,

00:29:54.114 --> 00:29:55.130
because, in fact,

00:29:55.130 --> 00:29:59.198
when he paints,
the artist is also in

00:29:59.198 --> 00:30:00.913
his own reality.

00:30:00.913 --> 00:30:03.464
And it's not the true reality of the East.

00:30:03.653 --> 00:30:05.993
We tell the children,
"if you're given information

00:30:05.993 --> 00:30:08.431
or if you're looking at a work of art

00:30:08.431 --> 00:30:09.914
you need to question it."

00:30:09.914 --> 00:30:12.088
"You mustn't take it at face value."

00:30:12.088 --> 00:30:15.177
And the images of women as well.

00:30:15.177 --> 00:30:18.431
Really, when you see the paintings

00:30:18.431 --> 00:30:21.564
the women are extremely sensual,
extremely erotic.

00:30:21.564 --> 00:30:24.368
And they show that even then

00:30:24.368 --> 00:30:26.877
women were boxed into that image.

00:30:26.877 --> 00:30:32.310
And today, when you watch television,
or in bus shelters

00:30:32.310 --> 00:30:36.744
there are still images of
very erotic women.

00:30:36.744 --> 00:30:41.903
And should we be looking at them
without questioning this?

00:30:41.903 --> 00:30:45.073
Because aren't women often shown

00:30:45.073 --> 00:30:47.083
as treasure to be won?

00:30:47.083 --> 00:30:50.636
And then there are also 
several rooms where

00:30:50.636 --> 00:30:52.149
we talk about disguises.

00:30:52.149 --> 00:30:54.199
When we use disguises.

00:30:54.199 --> 00:30:56.144
What are acceptable disguises?

00:30:56.144 --> 00:30:58.429
Do we know, for example

00:30:58.429 --> 00:31:02.749
that we can't use 
dark brown skin as a disguise?

00:31:02.749 --> 00:31:06.572
Some people think we can,
but we need to remember the history.

00:31:06.572 --> 00:31:08.690
And it also shows that

00:31:08.690 --> 00:31:13.691
there are some things you can't
overcome with a disguise.

00:31:13.691 --> 00:31:16.224
Then there is a book called
"My Black Stars"

00:31:16.224 --> 00:31:18.482
that I wrote a few years ago.

00:31:18.482 --> 00:31:20.955
In fact, it was really important to me

00:31:20.955 --> 00:31:25.824
because, I don't know
if it's the case here...

00:31:28.192 --> 00:31:31.366
Not you, madam.

00:31:32.387 --> 00:31:33.554
The two gentlemen there.

00:31:34.507 --> 00:31:37.779
The first timeâ€”I can tell that
you're not French just like that....

00:31:37.879 --> 00:31:40.056
the first time that you heard about

00:31:40.056 --> 00:31:42.510
the history of black people

00:31:42.510 --> 00:31:45.068
in your school curriculum, when was it?

00:31:46.934 --> 00:31:49.130
In secondary school? 
But what did they talk about?

00:31:53.830 --> 00:31:57.037
OK, you can't just repeat the same things,
that's not how it works.

00:31:57.037 --> 00:32:00.537
What is this history?
I wanted to say more about it.

00:32:01.639 --> 00:32:05.172
No, but really, 
we often don't realize this

00:32:05.172 --> 00:32:08.172
but the first time we here about
the history of black people

00:32:08.172 --> 00:32:10.196
it's through the history of slavery.

00:32:10.196 --> 00:32:12.821
And actually, it's shocking.

00:32:12.821 --> 00:32:14.741
When you are dark brown you say

00:32:14.741 --> 00:32:18.283
"Damn, what happened next? 
Where were they before?"

00:32:19.563 --> 00:32:23.767
And so, I said to myself,
I have to write a book

00:32:23.767 --> 00:32:25.829
that questions the public's perceptions.

00:32:25.829 --> 00:32:28.617
Because if everyone is made to
come at it from that angle

00:32:28.617 --> 00:32:31.873
that creates a way of seeing the world.

00:32:31.873 --> 00:32:35.213
And so the idea was to show that there
were men and women

00:32:35.213 --> 00:32:37.638
who could tell a 
different version of history.

00:32:37.638 --> 00:32:39.916
Because, again, we are all

00:32:39.916 --> 00:32:43.067
the product of a history
that we've been told.

00:32:43.907 --> 00:32:45.978
We can't escape that.

00:32:46.858 --> 00:32:49.144
But sometimes we don't realize how much

00:32:49.144 --> 00:32:52.356
this history actually
determines the way we think.

00:32:52.356 --> 00:32:57.454
And so the idea is to question this
way of thinking, question history.

00:32:57.454 --> 00:32:59.115
And to inform.

00:32:59.115 --> 00:33:02.239
And the funny thing was, because when I...

00:33:02.239 --> 00:33:04.654
I went on TV

00:33:04.654 --> 00:33:07.941
journalists would say, "Mr. Thuram

00:33:07.941 --> 00:33:10.579
I didn't know black people
had done so many things."

00:33:10.579 --> 00:33:12.907
Because the violence is so pervasive.

00:33:12.907 --> 00:33:15.339
Although I was pleased,
the violence is everywhere.

00:33:15.339 --> 00:33:18.757
And I even remember children 
saying to me in Togo:

00:33:18.757 --> 00:33:22.226
"Yeah, I thought that black people
hadn't done anything before."

00:33:22.226 --> 00:33:26.685
And so, it's essential
to tell their stories.

00:33:26.685 --> 00:33:30.193
and, actually, when
you look at your school curriculum

00:33:30.193 --> 00:33:31.264
there are very few men

00:33:31.264 --> 00:33:34.264
or women who have done
extraordinary things.

00:33:34.264 --> 00:33:35.264
What's more

00:33:35.264 --> 00:33:38.204
there are also very few women
in the school curriculum.

00:33:38.204 --> 00:33:40.977
That is very significant.

00:33:40.977 --> 00:33:45.005
So, the idea is always to try
to broaden our knowledge

00:33:45.005 --> 00:33:47.695
to change the way we think.

00:33:48.405 --> 00:33:49.933
That little scroll.

00:33:49.933 --> 00:33:52.537
I wanted to show you,
because once again

00:33:53.927 --> 00:33:56.303
the idea is to question.

00:33:56.303 --> 00:33:58.294
So, can you see this map?

00:34:01.172 --> 00:34:02.696
There was a movement there.

00:34:02.696 --> 00:34:04.138
Can you see the map or not?

00:34:05.948 --> 00:34:07.128
They cheated.

00:34:07.128 --> 00:34:08.400
OK.

00:34:08.750 --> 00:34:11.750
In fact, there were,
I'm not going to name names,

00:34:11.750 --> 00:34:14.750
some people have asked me to turn it over.

00:34:14.750 --> 00:34:17.853
And I often say, 
"have you ever seen a soccer ball?"

00:34:19.129 --> 00:34:20.674
You've never seen 
a soccer ball?

00:34:21.404 --> 00:34:23.928
You have seen a soccer ball?

00:34:23.928 --> 00:34:25.360
OK, thank you.

00:34:25.360 --> 00:34:27.509
I need interaction
otherwise it doesn't work.

00:34:27.509 --> 00:34:29.405
And the ball is round.

00:34:29.405 --> 00:34:31.368
You can't say the ball is upside down.

00:34:31.368 --> 00:34:35.947
However, as soon as we change our
way of looking at

00:34:35.947 --> 00:34:39.922
the world, we're told, no
we need to correct it

00:34:39.922 --> 00:34:41.339
because it is upside down.

00:34:41.339 --> 00:34:43.194
Really, it's just questioning

00:34:43.194 --> 00:34:47.004
our way of thinking about the world
and our customs.

00:34:47.004 --> 00:34:50.262
And the traditional maps you're used to

00:34:50.262 --> 00:34:52.172
often have Europe at the center

00:34:52.172 --> 00:34:54.148
and this is not by chance,
and what's more

00:34:54.148 --> 00:34:55.148
on traditional maps

00:34:55.148 --> 00:34:56.827
I don't know if you know

00:34:56.827 --> 00:35:00.465
they don't actually show the true
proportions of the continents.

00:35:00.465 --> 00:35:02.227
The scale is not right.

00:35:02.227 --> 00:35:04.067
And that is also very interesting.

00:35:04.067 --> 00:35:07.831
So, in effect, it's fixed.

00:35:08.761 --> 00:35:10.102
It's always the same.

00:35:10.102 --> 00:35:13.102
And I think that we need to
look for the complexity in things.

00:35:13.102 --> 00:35:16.715
And we often don't think about it
because we're not taught to do that.

00:35:16.715 --> 00:35:18.955
And so, with the map,
the children are the same

00:35:18.955 --> 00:35:20.533
they say, "that map isn't right."

00:35:20.533 --> 00:35:23.157
And, my son said to me the first time,

00:35:23.157 --> 00:35:25.120
"But, Dad, France isn't even on it.

00:35:25.120 --> 00:35:26.932
That's not right."

00:35:26.932 --> 00:35:29.061
Then when he saw how small
France was he said

00:35:29.061 --> 00:35:30.545
"No, that's not really France."

00:35:30.545 --> 00:35:33.594
He felt a little worse about himself.

00:35:33.594 --> 00:35:35.460
And really, that's the point.

00:35:35.460 --> 00:35:39.487
It's showing that, actually,
in our customs

00:35:39.487 --> 00:35:41.512
the ones we're brought up with

00:35:41.512 --> 00:35:43.779
there are some things
that are entrenched.

00:35:43.779 --> 00:35:46.220
And they're really stupid things

00:35:46.220 --> 00:35:49.652
like categorizing people based on
their skin color.

00:35:49.652 --> 00:35:53.791
One day when my son, Fred
â€”my second sonâ€”was four or five

00:35:54.958 --> 00:35:59.385
I said to him, "My love, tell me are
you the only black child in your class?"

00:36:00.420 --> 00:36:02.371
And the kid said, "I'm not black, Dad."

00:36:02.371 --> 00:36:03.181
And I thought

00:36:03.181 --> 00:36:05.736
"He has a problem,
he doesn't accept his color."

00:36:05.736 --> 00:36:09.265
"There's something there 
that we need to work through."

00:36:10.483 --> 00:36:12.290
I said, "Oh, you're not black?"

00:36:12.290 --> 00:36:14.630
He said, "Well no, I'm brown."

00:36:14.630 --> 00:36:16.838
I said, "Ah OK, but my dear,

00:36:16.838 --> 00:36:19.408
what color are the
other kids in your class?"

00:36:19.408 --> 00:36:21.576
He said, "They're pink."

00:36:22.738 --> 00:36:25.964
But it's very interesting as
when I play the game with the kids

00:36:25.964 --> 00:36:30.612
we're using categories
that aren't actually real.

00:36:31.782 --> 00:36:34.427
Because you, you're said
to be what? Black?

00:36:34.427 --> 00:36:35.741
I don't know, dark brown?

00:36:35.741 --> 00:36:38.242
OK, there you go!
But why are you giggling, madam?

00:36:39.715 --> 00:36:42.034
Because there are different
levels of black!

00:36:42.754 --> 00:36:44.223
And that's what's interesting.

00:36:44.223 --> 00:36:46.842
And I'll tell you another story
to really make you think

00:36:46.842 --> 00:36:49.067
about these false categories.

00:36:49.067 --> 00:36:51.235
One time, I walked into a bar

00:36:51.235 --> 00:36:54.404
And a man there said, "Mr. Thuram,

00:36:54.404 --> 00:36:57.369
a person of color was asking for you."

00:36:57.369 --> 00:36:59.049
I said, "Oh? A person of color?"

00:36:59.049 --> 00:37:01.811
"What color was he?"

00:37:02.282 --> 00:37:04.452
And he said, "Damn,
Thuram doesn't understand me."

00:37:04.452 --> 00:37:06.526
He said, "Well no,
he's a person of color!"

00:37:06.526 --> 00:37:08.500
I said,
"Yeah, but was he yellow or red?"

00:37:09.456 --> 00:37:11.041
And he just left. He gave up.

00:37:11.041 --> 00:37:13.895
This is just to show that we often
"use person of color"

00:37:13.895 --> 00:37:19.155
as if white wasn't a color.

00:37:19.155 --> 00:37:21.427
But, these categories are significant.

00:37:21.427 --> 00:37:22.903
They were created in the past

00:37:22.903 --> 00:37:25.887
and they mean they are colored,
they are not like us.

00:37:25.887 --> 00:37:28.223
They can't have the same rights as us.

00:37:28.223 --> 00:37:31.031
It's never an accident
when we talk about us and them.

00:37:31.031 --> 00:37:32.618
That means something.

00:37:32.618 --> 00:37:35.365
It means some people are delegitimized.

00:37:35.365 --> 00:37:38.163
They don't need the same rights as us.

00:37:38.163 --> 00:37:39.722
That's it.

00:37:39.722 --> 00:37:42.010
I'll ask one last question
as it's one p.m. and

00:37:42.010 --> 00:37:44.388
I'd like to pass the
microphone to my colleagues.

00:37:44.388 --> 00:37:47.440
When we were preparing the talk,
you said, "I'm not claiming to be the voice of truth,

00:37:47.440 --> 00:37:48.960
I just want us to move forward together."

00:37:48.960 --> 00:37:51.484
So, if we move forward together,
how can we help you?

00:37:51.484 --> 00:37:52.942
How can we contribute?

00:37:52.942 --> 00:37:55.942
And when I say we, I'm talking about
the people here, Googlers,

00:37:55.942 --> 00:37:58.056
but also beyond that, how do you work

00:37:58.056 --> 00:38:01.139
with people who aren't part
of the foundation?

00:38:01.139 --> 00:38:02.957
Look, there's the foundation director,

00:38:02.957 --> 00:38:05.587
if he can be of technical assistance,
or I don't know,

00:38:05.587 --> 00:38:09.583
but for me the idea is for each of us
to be able to ask questions

00:38:09.583 --> 00:38:12.911
about ourselves and the people around us.

00:38:12.911 --> 00:38:15.911
Because really,
sometimes we don't ask questions

00:38:15.911 --> 00:38:18.911
or sometimes we hear certain things,
and we don't call people out

00:38:18.911 --> 00:38:21.134
by saying, "Listen, you can't say that."

00:38:21.134 --> 00:38:23.184
"That needs to change, that's not right."

00:38:23.184 --> 00:38:26.391
And we tend to think that
as individuals, we can't do anything.

00:38:26.391 --> 00:38:30.694
But we can. Just paying attention
to your own behavior

00:38:30.694 --> 00:38:36.477
and also having the courage
to confront your own prejudices.

00:38:36.477 --> 00:38:38.845
Because some people say,
"No, I'm not prejudiced."

00:38:38.845 --> 00:38:41.123
No, every one of us has prejudices

00:38:41.123 --> 00:38:43.410
and prejudices are very important

00:38:43.410 --> 00:38:47.724
for humans. Because we need to act fast.

00:38:47.724 --> 00:38:50.124
They are thoughts...
so prejudices are sort of a

00:38:50.124 --> 00:38:51.894
quick... they help us think quickly.

00:38:51.894 --> 00:38:54.963
So, sometimes, that can cause us to do
stupid things.

00:38:54.963 --> 00:38:57.581
So, pay attention. That's the first thing.

00:38:57.581 --> 00:38:59.236
That's how you can help me.

00:38:59.236 --> 00:39:01.748
- I'd be very happy to do that. Easily.
-Yeah, yeah.

