film out at the moment, about Barnum.

00:53:23.909 --> 00:53:26.431
- You know who he is? OK.
- Yeah.

00:53:26.431 --> 00:53:28.460
- The Greatest Showman.
- OK.

00:53:28.460 --> 00:53:31.689
You need to know that not so long ago,

00:53:31.689 --> 00:53:34.230
we exhibited people in the zoo.

00:53:34.230 --> 00:53:36.432
Black people,

00:53:36.432 --> 00:53:40.746
Native Americans,
Orientals, as they called them, in fact

00:53:40.746 --> 00:53:44.023
for many Europeans, the first time
they saw these types of people

00:53:44.023 --> 00:53:45.153
was at the zoo.

00:53:45.153 --> 00:53:47.281
But, maybe you didn't know that.

00:53:47.281 --> 00:53:51.896
But that went on for a long time

00:53:51.896 --> 00:53:55.234
and that created a culture of viewing
people as exhibits.

00:53:55.234 --> 00:53:57.559
And recently, we went to

00:53:57.559 --> 00:54:01.039
I think it was the zoo
in Cologne, in Germany,

00:54:01.039 --> 00:54:03.154
and over the entrance

00:54:03.931 --> 00:54:05.827
there were animals and humans.

00:54:05.827 --> 00:54:07.614
Meaning, by walking through that door

00:54:07.614 --> 00:54:09.924
you could see animals and humans.

00:54:09.924 --> 00:54:11.949
In the Jardin d'Acclimatation in Paris

00:54:11.949 --> 00:54:15.270
they used to have human exhibits.

00:54:15.270 --> 00:54:18.470
By the way, I believe Christian Karembeu's

00:54:18.470 --> 00:54:22.530
great-grandparents were exhibited there.

00:54:22.530 --> 00:54:25.736
But, we are the products of that history.

00:54:25.736 --> 00:54:30.408
So, the way we look at people 
is significant.

00:54:30.408 --> 00:54:31.769
It comes from somewhere.

00:54:31.769 --> 00:54:34.761
And if they present

00:54:34.761 --> 00:54:36.962
people to you as savages

00:54:36.962 --> 00:54:38.652
you're going to believe it's true.

00:54:38.652 --> 00:54:41.193
And that's a cultural thing.

00:54:42.974 --> 00:54:46.325
And so when you come
across them outside of the zoo

00:54:46.325 --> 00:54:48.138
you're going to be a bit frightened.

00:54:48.138 --> 00:54:51.322
One thing I find remarkable,
that makes me wonder, is...

00:54:51.322 --> 00:54:53.708
They say that diversity scares people.

00:54:54.878 --> 00:54:58.116
Do you agree that diversity isn't scary?

00:54:59.258 --> 00:55:01.059
Maybe you are, a little.

00:55:01.169 --> 00:55:03.459
- Why me?
- I don't know.

00:55:03.459 --> 00:55:05.141
It's because I'm in the front row.

00:55:05.141 --> 00:55:08.748
But, they frequently say,
"diversity scares people."

00:55:08.748 --> 00:55:11.865
But when you are at the station,
or on a train

00:55:11.865 --> 00:55:14.205
you don't know the other people.

00:55:14.205 --> 00:55:17.047
There are people who are scared.
Take me as an example.

00:55:17.047 --> 00:55:21.694
When I was a young player
a very long time ago

00:55:22.851 --> 00:55:27.251
with my teammates who had dark-brown skin

00:55:27.251 --> 00:55:29.084
we knew that other people were afraid.

00:55:29.084 --> 00:55:30.667
I don't know why.

00:55:30.667 --> 00:55:33.097
I don't know why, because nobody had said,

00:55:33.097 --> 00:55:34.381
"Careful, they're afraid."

00:55:34.381 --> 00:55:37.222
But from the way they acted,
we knew that they were afraid.

00:55:37.222 --> 00:55:38.860
We knew it.

00:55:40.058 --> 00:55:42.985
Nobody had explained it to us,
but in our heads

00:55:42.985 --> 00:55:45.695
we said, "they're afraid of black people."

00:55:46.695 --> 00:55:48.262
Not you, madam.

00:55:48.262 --> 00:55:50.533
But that's how it was, do you see?

00:55:50.533 --> 00:55:53.447
And so, really, it's education.

00:55:53.447 --> 00:55:56.709
And that's why I think we need to
focus our efforts

00:55:56.709 --> 00:56:00.891
on children, because they
are less conditioned.

00:56:00.891 --> 00:56:04.853
When I talk about certain 
things with my mother

00:56:04.853 --> 00:56:06.435
it's surreal.

00:56:06.435 --> 00:56:08.415
When she was at school, they taught her

00:56:08.415 --> 00:56:10.197
that her ancestors were Gauls.

00:56:10.197 --> 00:56:12.644
I asked my mother,
"How could you believe that?"

00:56:12.644 --> 00:56:14.585
There's a problem there, right?

00:56:14.585 --> 00:56:17.625
She said, 
"But, that's what we learned at school."

00:56:17.625 --> 00:56:20.250
So, we need to question 
the things we learn in school.

00:56:20.250 --> 00:56:22.678
They might teach us some
strange things in school

00:56:22.678 --> 00:56:25.068
even nowadays, right?

00:56:25.068 --> 00:56:26.455
Christopher Columbus?

00:56:28.895 --> 00:56:31.176
What's your ethnic origin, madam?

00:56:31.500 --> 00:56:33.515
You shouldn't sit in the front row.

00:56:33.515 --> 00:56:36.445
Central African?
Who discovered Central Africa?

00:56:37.012 --> 00:56:38.610
Oh, you don't know?

00:56:38.610 --> 00:56:40.489
It was Christopher Columbus.

00:56:41.194 --> 00:56:42.688
Did you not know that?

00:56:42.688 --> 00:56:44.531
It's an interesting example

00:56:44.531 --> 00:56:47.907
to help us understand.
That's why I tell the story,

00:56:49.313 --> 00:56:53.070
I think it was the
Treaty of Berlin in 1865

00:56:53.070 --> 00:56:54.910
when Africa was divided up.

00:56:54.910 --> 00:56:56.527
Had you heard of that?

00:56:56.527 --> 00:56:59.268
OK, but that's interesting to know.

00:56:59.268 --> 00:57:03.883
And the problems, the power relations

00:57:03.883 --> 00:57:07.003
between Europe and Africa
still exist today.

00:57:07.003 --> 00:57:08.355
We mustn't be naive.

00:57:08.355 --> 00:57:11.406
These power relations still exist.

00:57:11.406 --> 00:57:14.575
And, really, we need to question them

00:57:14.575 --> 00:57:17.456
because I think these power relations

00:57:17.456 --> 00:57:20.898
whether that's during slavery
or as part of modern colonization

00:57:20.898 --> 00:57:23.652
come from a small number of people.

00:57:24.589 --> 00:57:26.580
But that depends on the discussion.

00:57:26.580 --> 00:57:30.453
The exhibition that we put on
about the East...

00:57:30.453 --> 00:57:34.247
even today there's an element of fantasy
in the way we talk about the East.

00:57:35.537 --> 00:57:38.496
Even we end up believing in it.

00:57:38.496 --> 00:57:40.343
And that's the thing.

00:57:40.343 --> 00:57:42.457
It's taking time to ask ourselves,

00:57:42.457 --> 00:57:46.347
"Am I looking at the world

00:57:46.347 --> 00:57:48.087
in the right way?"

00:57:48.087 --> 00:57:50.057
But we often don't ask that question.

00:57:50.057 --> 00:57:53.156
For you, coming from Central Africa,
it's not the same?

00:57:53.156 --> 00:57:56.780
Right? What do people see
when they look at Central Africa?

00:57:56.780 --> 00:57:59.272
Nothing? Really?

00:57:59.272 --> 00:58:02.679
She's not answering me, 
she's having trouble.

00:58:02.679 --> 00:58:04.679
Another question.

00:58:04.679 --> 00:58:08.345
Thank you very much,
it's 33 minutes past, I know you all..

00:58:08.345 --> 00:58:11.419
Thank you.

00:58:11.419 --> 00:58:12.903
Thank you.

